SIMPLE: turmeric
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turmeric
<hw>Tur"mer*ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>terre-m⟦eacute⟧rite</ets>, NL. <ets>terramerita</ets>,
<ets>turmerica</ets>; apparently meaning, excellent earth, but perhaps a
corruption of Ar. <ets>kurkum</ets>. Cf. <er>Curcuma</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An East Indian plant of the genus
<gen>Curcuma</gen>, of the Ginger family.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The root or rootstock of the <spn>Curcuma
longa</spn>. It is externally grayish, but internally of a deep, lively
yellow or saffron color, and has a slight aromatic smell, and a
bitterish, slightly acrid taste. It is used for a dye, a medicine, a
condiment, and a chemical test.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turmeric</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Turmeric
<hw>Tur"mer*ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of or
pertaining to turmeric; resembling, or obtained from, turmeric; specif.,
designating an acid obtained by the oxidation of turmerol.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Turmeric paper</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>paper
impregnated with turmeric and used as a test for alkaline substances, by
which it is changed from yellow to brown.</cd> -- <col><b>Turmeric
root</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Bloodroot.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Orangeroot.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turmerol</ent>⟦br⟧
